    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-05-03T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-05-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="726"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d726">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/10828</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation, by the Assistant Chief
                        of the Division of Near Eastern Affairs</hi> (<hi rend="italic"
                    >Alling</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-05-03">May 3,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Colonel Cox<note n="11" xml:id="d726fn11">Lt Col. Walter Cox, Military
                        Intelligence Division, War Department.</note> telephoned today to say he
                    thought we might be interested in knowing that MID had just been informed by
                    General von Boetticher, the German Military Attaché, that German forces had
                    occupied the following islands in the Aegean Sea: Skyros, Myconas, Nikaria and
                    Suda. Colonel Cox said that MID had been able to identify the first three
                    islands, but they could not identify Suda. Upon investigation it appears likely
                    that the island in question is probably Syros, but this is not certain.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
